{"cursor":"16672","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Ethnic group |image =  |group = Abayudaya\n|poptime = '2,000' (estimate)\n[http://bechollashon.org/projects/abayudaya/abayudaya.php] |popplace =\nUganda:   '2,000' (estimate) |langs = Luganda, Lusoga, Lugwere,\nHebrew |rels = Judaism |related =\nTradition : Jews   African Jews    &n-\nbsp;'Abayudaya' [[Ethnobiology]] :   Baganda, Bagwere,\nBasoga    'Abayudaya' }}\n\n\n\nThe 'Abayudaya' (Abayudaya is Luganda for \"People of Judah\", Berg, Irwin M.\n(January 1997) \"Among the Abayudaya\". Commentary Vol. 103(1) pp. 52-\n4. [http://www.vetssweatshop.net/uganda.htm Pomerance, Rachel.\n\"Uganda's Jews finally have their day at the Mikvah]  analogous to\nChildren of Israel) are a Baganda community in eastern Uganda near the town of\nMbale who practice Judaism. Although they are not genetically or historically\nrelated to other ethnic Jews, they are devout in their practice of the religion,\nkeeping their version of kashrut, and observing Shabbat. There are several\ndifferent villages where the Ugandan Jews live. Most of these are recognized by\nthe Reform and Conservative movements of Judaism. However, the villagers of\nPutti are still seeking an Orthodox conversion and practice strict Rabbinical\nJudaism. [http://www.thejewsofuganda.org/history.php The\nCommittee To Save Ugandan Jewry - A First Hand Account of The History of the\nAbayudaya]\n\nTheir population is estimated at approximately 2,000 having once been as large\nas 3,000 (prior to the persecutions of the Idi Amin regime); like their\nneighbors, they are subsistence farmers. Most Abayudaya are of Bagwere origin,\nexcept for those from Namutumba who are Basoga. They speak Luganda, Lusoga or\nLugwere, although some have learned Hebrew as well.\n","linknr":401,"url":"Abayudaya","recorded":1375089022,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Abayudaya&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Abayudaya&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/ope